	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Trade policy: SACU-India agreement progressing</h1>

			
			<h4>
												26 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>SACU and Indian officials are due to meet in the first week of October 2010 to discuss outstanding issues in the finalisation of the India-SACU preferential trade agreement, negotiations for which were first launched in July 2007. Currently India-SACU trade is expanding and is expected to reach US$10 billion in 2011. </p><p>Another important trend for the SACU is the evolution of its trade with the EU. Eurostat reports that, following a major expansion of EU27-South Africa trade from €26.5 billion in 2000 to €42.6 billion in 2008, trade fell sharply in 2009. While EU exports to South Africa grew from 2000 to 2008 by 71%, and EU imports from South Africa grew by 52%, in 2009 EU exports dropped by one-fifth, while EU imports from South Africa fell by one-third, although the diamond trade played a major role in this decline (-37% in the value of South Africa exports between 2008 and 2009). The decreases which occurred in EU-South Africa trade were bigger than the decreases seen in total extra-EU exports (-16%) and imports (-23%). From 2008 to 2009, EU imports of fruit and vegetables fell by 12%, but still represented 8% of total EU imports form South Africa in 2009. The bulk of these imports were fresh grapes, oranges, apples and pears.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Press Information Bureau, Government of India, ‘Finalisation of India-SACU Preferential Trade Agreement soon’, 31 August 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://pib.nic.in/release/release.asp?relid=65459" target="_self">http://pib.nic.in/release/release.asp?relid=65459</a> </p><p>Eurostat, ‘EU27 trade with South Africa fell sharply in 2009’, Statistics in Focus, 42/2010 </p><p>
<a href="http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/cache/ITY_OFFPUB/KS-SF-10-042/EN/KS-SF-10-042-EN.PDF" target="_self">http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/cache/ITY_OFFPUB/KS-SF-10-042/EN/KS-SF-...</a> </p><p><i>Thisisafricaonline.com</i>, ‘South-South trade risks reinforcing commodity dependence’, 18 June 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://web.thisisafricaonline.com/2010/06/18/unctad-south-south-trade-risks-reinforcing-commodity-dependence/" target="_self">http://web.thisisafricaonline.com/2010/06/18/unctad-south-south-trade-ri...</a> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The recent decline in the value of South Africa exports to the EU highlights the continued concentration of South African exports to the EU in primary commodities. This provides important background to why South Africa accords such high priority to the development of trade relations with advanced developing countries. It is hoped that the development of South-South trade will help to promote a structural transformation of South Africa’s export profile, with a far greater volume of exports of value-added products being stimulated. This is why so much importance is being attached to the MFN clause issue in the EPA negotiations.</p><p>However it should be noted that a recent UNCTAD report has suggested that South-South trade may well be reinforcing Africa’s dependence on basic commodity exports. Such trends need to be reversed if these new trade relationships are to promote economic diversification. </p><p>Thus we find that from the SACU perspective, the primary interest in the SACU-India negotiations is in gaining access to the huge Indian market, which for many years was highly protected. However, the sheer scale of Indian production is a major source of concern. </p><p>Against this background, the aim has always been not to conclude a free-trade area agreement, but rather a preferential trade agreement with more limited product coverage (perhaps covering between 500 and 1,000 tariff lines). In this context, analysts have suggested that given the trade expansion which is already under way, it is doubtful whether a SACU-India preferential trade agreement will bring any meaningful changes to the current volume and structure of trade between SACU and India.</p>
		</div>
		
